# Opti-Route Project Roadmap

## Sprint 1 – Setup & Exploration (Due 11/10)
**Goals:** Set up project and gather references  
- [ ] Turn in Exercise 6 and list project in Teams Spreadsheet  
- [ ] Join KSU-IS GitHub organization  
- [ ] Create GitHub repo under KSU-IS (public, add README, add MIT license)  
- [ ] Edit and commit README.md with project description  
- [ ] Explore one Python route-planning repo  
  - Example: https://github.com/aram-ap/python-route-planner  
  - Read code and attempt to run it  
- [ ] Update projectroadmap.md with notes/findings from reference repo  

**Deliverables:** GitHub repo with README & roadmap, Exercise 6 completed  

---

## Sprint 2 – Core Functionality
**Goals:** Build main features and track progress  
- [ ] Implement origin/destination input page  
- [ ] Add route type options: fastest, scenic, beginner-friendly, fuel-efficient  
- [ ] Code algorithm to calculate and compare routes  
- [ ] Commit at least 6 meaningful code changes with descriptive messages  
- [ ] Test multiple routes and debug issues  
- [ ] Update roadmap with new tasks or mark completed items  

**Deliverables:** Working prototype, visible GitHub commits, updated roadmap  

---

## Sprint 3 – Refinement & Presentation
**Goals:** Refine project, add optional UI, and prepare presentation  
- [ ] Add optional map visualization (e.g., folium or matplotlib)  
- [ ] Display estimated travel times and directions clearly  
- [ ] Ensure routes adapt to user preferences (safety, fun, efficiency)  
- [ ] Continue committing meaningful code changes  
- [ ] Finalize README.md with full description and screenshots  
- [ ] Create and upload PowerPoint slide:  
  - Project title, team members, tagline, optional screenshots/images  
  - Upload to D2L and GitHub repo  

**Deliverables:** Fully functional Opti-Route, final README & roadmap, PPT slide
